President Barack Obama issued a proclamation expressing his condolences on the death of Nelson Mandela. He described Mandela as a close friend, an incomparable liberator, and an inspiration for freedom, justice, and human dignity. Obama highlighted Mandela's achievements and his journey from prisoner to president, emphasizing his commitment to reconciliation and the example he set for humanity. The president called on people to carry forward Mandela's legacy by making decisions guided by love, recognizing the impact of one person, and striving for a future worthy of his sacrifice. As a mark of respect, Obama ordered that the flag of the United States be flown at half-staff at various locations until December 9, 2013.